              data-srcset="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/rvulI6sB4BNxGbOf0gz7k7fIT9iC-M_vMB9A3sy7_5cnknIE0p7OdmrE56qTiNre99Bm1rMnXctrhIYOjnXuV84ALIjM=w680-h480-c 480w, https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/rvulI6sB4BNxGbOf0gz7k7fIT9iC-M_vMB9A3sy7_5cnknIE0p7OdmrE56qTiNre99Bm1rMnXctrhIYOjnXuV84ALIjM=w1360-h960-c 2x" alt="Transfixing: Soundstreams presents Tan Dun&#39;s Water Passion"
              ></picture><span class="post--meta"><em class="post--meta-date">March 13, 2018</em><em class="post--meta-author">Greg Finney</em><em class="post--meta-category">Review</em></span></a><p class="post--list-desc">Michelle Colton, Aiyun Huang, and Ryan Scott showed what true musical versatility means, playing timpani, water (yes, they actually played the water - sometimes with cups to create a neat effect that reminded me of horses galloping through water), cymbals (which they would then dip in the water to create new effects), singing prayer bowls and that&#39;s just in the first two movements.</p><a href="/transfixing-soundstreams-presents-tan-duns-water-passion/" class="btn post--button">Read More</a></li><li><a href="/levines-ugly-exit-the-disposable-met/" class="post--list-title"><h1>Levine&#39;s ugly exit, &amp; the disposable Met</h1></a><a href="/levines-ugly-exit-the-disposable-met/" class="post--list-image"><picture><!-- <source srcset="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/2DfHGdkJ3HogrfiBbNvOvfVtOt2eRmDfifdr87mE1qv7JB7Ae56OssJOitjHcSupp6c7DAZHzqQxNPWeSncrS7g1B1298g=w680-h480-c 480w, https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/2DfHGdkJ3HogrfiBbNvOvfVtOt2eRmDfifdr87mE1qv7JB7Ae56OssJOitjHcSupp6c7DAZHzqQxNPWeSncrS7g1B1298g=w1360-h960-c 2x" media="(min-width: 40em)"> --><img
